<TITLE> Futures point up; lower commodities to help </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW YORK, March 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - US stock futures pointed to a higher opening on Thursday as sharp falls in prices of oil and other commodities gave some relief to investors worried about their effect on consumer and business spending. While the recent declines might hurt shares of energy and other companies, as they did on Wednesday, they are expected to be a positive for the broader market, analysts said, especially for companies like such as big manufacturers. In earnings news, after the close, shares of Nike Inc jumped about 5 percent to $64.59 as the company posted a third-quarter profit that handily beat Wall Street's estimates. "What's happening in gold and oil and commodities generally is there are a lot of hedge funds raising capital, and it might be temporary, but it should help relieve some of the pressure in equities," said Peter Cardillo, chief market economist at Avalon Partners in New York. "It's also the last day ahead of a long weekend," so short-covering could be seen as well, he said. S&P 500 futures were up 7.2 points and were above fair value, a formula to evaluate pricing taking into account interest rates, dividends and time to expiration on the contract. Dow Jones industrial average futures rose 28 points, and Nasdaq 100 futures gained 8.25 points. The economic agenda includes Labor Department first-time claims for jobless benefits for the week ended March 15 at 8:30 a.m. (1230 GMT). Economists in a Reuters survey forecast 360,000 new filings compared with 353,000 in the prior week. Stocks fell on Wednesday as plunging gold and oil prices drove energy and mining shares lower, and speculation that Merrill Lynch & Co may need to take more write-downs deflated growing optimism that the credit crisis was abati
